Your font is rendered based on the image quality, a good way in my opinion is to multiply the font with a factor to resize it based on the image size, the following function might help you 

    /**
     * compute a factor for different image qualities
     *
     * @param image the image to compute the factor
     * @param coefficient to scale the factor
     * @return
     */
    private static double getImageFactor(BufferedImage image, int coefficient) {
        Dimension screenSize = Toolkit.getDefaultToolkit().getScreenSize();
        double screenSizeWidth = screenSize.getWidth();
        double screenSizeHeight = screenSize.getHeight();
        double screenHypotenuse = Math.sqrt(screenSizeWidth * screenSizeWidth + screenSizeHeight * screenSizeHeight);

        Rectangle bounds = image.getData().getBounds();
        double imageWidth = bounds.getWidth();
        double imageHeight = bounds.getHeight();
        double imageHypotenuse = Math.sqrt(imageWidth * imageWidth + imageHeight * imageHeight);

        return imageHypotenuse * coefficient / (screenHypotenuse + screenHypotenuse);
    }

