Helpfully, getting a filtered list of objects from an array can be done using [the `$filter` operator](https://www.mongodb.com/docs/manual/reference/operator/aggregation/filter/). The operator takes an array as input and can process each item individually via an expression. In your situation that expression would include a `$regexMatch` to look for the value in the string(s) of interest. So the stage would look something like this:

```
  {
    &quot;$addFields&quot;: {
      hobbies: {
        $filter: {
          input: &quot;$hobbies&quot;,
          cond: {
            $or: [
              {
                $regexMatch: {
                  input: &quot;$$this.name&quot;,
                  regex: &quot;d&quot;,
                  options: &quot;i&quot;
                }
              },
              {
                $regexMatch: {
                  input: &quot;$$this.description&quot;,
                  regex: &quot;d&quot;,
                  options: &quot;i&quot;
                }
              }
            ]
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }
```

Sample Mongo Playground example is [here](https://mongoplayground.net/p/uMrNtU2osCq).

From your question it&#39;s not quite clear if you will separately be using this as selection criteria for the document itself.  I&#39;ve left the leading `$match` stage to just use `_id` for the moment, but of course you can add any other filters to it (such as `&#39;hobbies.name&#39;: /d/i`) as needed.

I&#39;m not personally familiar enough with Spring Boot to say what the exact syntax is to create such a pipeline, but I do know that aggregations are supported.

